JOHANNESBURG - Archbishop Emeritus Desmond Tutu was one of the high-profile mourners who visited the late Winnie Madikizela-Mandela’s home in Soweto on Thursday. The ANC stalwart died at a Johannesburg hospital on Easter Monday aged 81. The Tutus and Mandelas were once neighbours for years in Orlando's world -amous Vilakazi Street . READ: ANC to launch Winnie Madikizela-Mandela Day of Service Tutu’s office said he and his wife, Leah, who now reside in Cape Town, travelled to Gauteng to convey their condolences to Madikizela-Mandela’s family. They were accompanied to the Soweto home by the CEO of the Nelson Mandela Foundation, Sello Hatang, and his wife, Thembi Hatang. Tutu has previously described Madikizela-Mandela “as a defining symbol of the struggle against apartheid who refused to be bowed by the imprisonment of her husband, the harassment of her family by security forces, detentions, bannings or banishment”. READ: Politics is not for sissies: De Lille pays tribute to Madikizela-Mandela The Zulu Royal House, representing King Goodwill Zwelithini, were also present at the Soweto residence. The delegation arrived with four cows.  National Freedom Party leader Zanele Magwaza-Msibi and NFP member of Parliament Professor Nhlanhla Khubisa were also present. Madikizela-Mandela will be laid to rest on Saturday. eNCA